author: Nilesh Kadivar

text:
For Second Part,

In MSSQL, this can be used:

WITH T1 AS (
    select *,
    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY order_id) AS RowNumber,
    DATEADD(day,-ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY order_id),order_date) AS DIFF
    FROM orders    
),
T2 AS (
    SELECT *,count(*) over(partition by DIFF) as no_of_records
    FROM T1
)
SELECT *
FROM T2
WHERE no_of_records=3;


Thank you :)

text:
I think you have a logic error in first example, because your solution depends on fact that ID numbers are consecutive which might not be a case. For instance, you can have someone deleted one of records ((lets say I deleted row where ID = 3 ) and then your ID sequence will not be consecutive, but it will be 1,2,4,5 .... So the code will not work for this situation and those are still consecutive records.
Here is an example in which will it happen:

with temperatures as (
	select * from (values
	(1,'London',-1,'2021-01-01'),
	(2,'London',-3,'2021-01-02'),
	(4,'London',-1,'2021-01-03'),
	(5,'London',1,'2021-01-04'),
	(6,'London',-3,'2021-01-05'),
	(7,'London',-2,'2021-01-06')
	) as i (id,city,temperature,day)
)
select 
	*,
	row_number() over (order by id) rn,
	id - row_number() over (order by id) as difference
from temperatures where temperature < 0

and result:

"id"	"city"	"temperature"	"day"               	"rn"	"difference"
1	"London"	-1	                "2021-01-01"	          1	0
2	"London"	-3	                "2021-01-02"        	  2	0
4	"London"	-1	                "2021-01-03"	          3	1
6	"London"	-3	                "2021-01-05"	          4	2
7	"London"	-2	                "2021-01-06"	          5	2

Row with ID =4 shoukd have difference 0 so your solution will work, but this is not the case as you can see it in example above.

¬†@techTFQ¬† I do not want to start a flame, just that some rookie will take this as granted, and I wanted to actually help them. I know that there was 3 scenarios, but than you should mention that this works only in situation when there are no gaps in ID sequence. in MSSQL, you can use the dateadd function to do this. Try the below query:

SELECT *,
DATEADD(DAY , -1 * (ROW_NUMBER() OVER(ORDER BY order_id) ) , order_date)  AS diff
 FROM orders;
